{
  "What is the most powerful agent of erosion worldwide?": "",
  "Gravity": "",
  "Ice": "",
  "Running water": "",
  "Wind": "",
  "Running water, including rivers, streams, and surface runoff, erodes and transports more sediment than any other agent globally, shaping landscapes from mountains to coastlines.": "",
  "Deposition occurs when a transporting agent:": "",
  "Speeds up and gains energy": "",
  "Loses energy and can no longer carry its sediment load": "",
  "Reverses direction suddenly": "",
  "Encounters harder bedrock": "",
  "When a transporting agent such as a river, wind, or glacier slows down or loses energy, it can no longer carry its sediment load, and particles are deposited in order from largest to smallest.": "",
  "When sediment is deposited by water, which particles settle out first?": "",
  "Clay particles": "",
  "Large particles such as gravel and sand": "",
  "Silt particles": "",
  "All particles settle at the same rate regardless of size": "",
  "Larger, heavier particles require more energy to stay in transport and are deposited first as water slows, while finer particles like clay remain suspended longer and travel farther before settling.": "",
  "Where does a delta form?": "",
  "At the top of a mountain where a river begins": "",
  "Where a glacier retreats from a valley": "",
  "Where two rivers merge into one larger stream": "",
  "Where a river enters a lake or ocean and deposits its sediment": "",
  "Deltas form when rivers reach standing water, abruptly slow down, and deposit their sediment load in a characteristic fan or triangular shape at the river's mouth.": "",
  "Glaciers are unique erosion agents because they can:": "",
  "Only erode during the summer months": "",
  "Move material uphill against gravity": "",
  "Only work on flat, level surfaces": "",
  "Transport enormous boulders and carve U-shaped valleys": "",
  "Glaciers have immense mass and can transport boulders weighing thousands of tons, carving wide U-shaped valleys through abrasion and plucking as they flow slowly downhill.": "",
  "Wind erosion is most effective in which type of environment?": "",
  "Deep ocean floors": "",
  "Dense forests with heavy rainfall": "",
  "Wetlands with standing water": "",
  "Dry environments with little vegetation, such as deserts": "",
  "Wind erosion is most effective in arid environments where dry, loose particles lack the protection of vegetation or moisture, allowing wind to easily pick up and transport fine sediment.": "",
  "How do glaciers erode the landscape?": "",
  "By abrasion and plucking": "",
  "By oxidizing minerals in the bedrock": "",
  "By melting only the softest rock types": "",
  "By dissolving rock through chemical reactions": "",
  "Glaciers erode through abrasion, where rocks embedded in the ice grind against the bedrock like sandpaper, and through plucking, where the ice freezes onto rock and pulls fragments away as it moves.": "",
  "What role does vegetation play in controlling erosion?": "",
  "Vegetation increases erosion by loosening soil": "",
  "Vegetation has no effect on erosion rates": "",
  "Vegetation only affects chemical weathering, not erosion": "",
  "Plant roots hold soil in place and slow erosion significantly": "",
  "Plant roots bind soil particles together and absorb excess water, while leaves and stems break the impact of raindrops, all of which dramatically reduce the rate of erosion on vegetated slopes.": "",
  "The Grand Canyon was primarily formed by:": "",
  "Wind erosion over millions of years": "",
  "Water erosion by the Colorado River over millions of years": "",
  "A single massive flood event": "",
  "Glacial erosion during the last ice age": "",
  "The Colorado River has been cutting through layers of rock for approximately 5 to 6 million years, carving the Grand Canyon over a mile deep through persistent water erosion.": "",
  "A moraine is a feature created by which agent of erosion and deposition?": "",
  "Rivers": "",
  "Glaciers": "",
  "Ocean waves": "",
  "Moraines are ridges or mounds of unsorted glacial debris (till) deposited along the edges or at the terminus of a glacier, marking the former extent of ice advance.": "",
  "What is erosion?": "",
  "The transport of weathered material by natural agents such as water, wind, ice, or gravity": "",
  "The in-place breakdown of rock by chemical reactions": "",
  "The formation of new rock from cooling magma": "",
  "The compaction and cementation of sediment into rock": "",
  "Erosion is the process by which weathered rock and soil particles are picked up and moved from one location to another by natural agents including flowing water, wind, glacial ice, and gravity.": "",
  "What is deposition?": "",
  "The process by which eroded sediment is dropped or settles in a new location when the transporting agent loses energy": "",
  "The formation of metamorphic rock under heat and pressure": "",
  "The breaking down of rock into smaller pieces": "",
  "The melting of glacial ice into meltwater streams": "",
  "Deposition is the laying down of sediment that was being carried by an erosional agent, occurring when the agent loses energy and can no longer transport its load, building up new landforms over time.": "",
  "What is loess?": "",
  "A glacial lake formed behind a moraine dam": "",
  "A type of volcanic rock formed from cooled lava": "",
  "A river channel carved into soft sedimentary rock": "",
  "Fine-grained silt deposited by wind over large areas, forming very fertile soil": "",
  "Loess is wind-deposited silt, often originating from glacial outwash plains or desert surfaces, that accumulates in thick layers to form some of the most fertile agricultural soils in the world.": "",
  "What is an alluvial fan?": "",
  "A ridge of glacial debris at the end of a glacier": "",
  "A deposit of wind-blown sand in a desert": "",
  "A fan-shaped deposit of sediment that forms where a stream exits a mountain valley onto a flat plain": "",
  "A type of coastal sand dune": "",
  "Alluvial fans form at the base of mountains where fast-flowing streams suddenly lose gradient and spread out across a flat plain, depositing sediment in a broad fan shape as the water slows.": "",
  "What does 'longshore drift' mean?": "",
  "The movement of tectonic plates along a coastline": "",
  "The offshore movement of sediment by deep ocean currents": "",
  "The zigzag movement of sand along a beach caused by waves hitting the shore at an angle": "",
  "The gradual sinking of a coastline due to erosion": "",
  "Longshore drift is the transport of sand and sediment along a coastline in a zigzag pattern caused by waves approaching the beach at an angle, carrying sand up the beach diagonally and then pulling it straight back down.": "",
  "What is a barrier island?": "",
  "A volcanic island formed by an underwater eruption": "",
  "A long, narrow island of sand deposited parallel to the coast by wave action": "",
  "An island formed by coral reef growth": "",
  "A rocky island carved by glacial erosion": "",
  "Barrier islands are elongated sand deposits created by wave action and longshore drift that run parallel to the mainland coast, protecting the shore and creating sheltered lagoons behind them.": "",
  "What does 'abrasion' mean in the context of erosion?": "",
  "The grinding and wearing away of rock surfaces by friction from transported particles": "",
  "The cracking of rock due to temperature changes": "",
  "The dissolving of rock by chemical reactions with water": "",
  "The lifting of loose particles by strong wind gusts": "",
  "Abrasion is the physical wearing down of rock surfaces caused by the friction of sediment particles carried by water, wind, or ice scraping against the bedrock, similar to the effect of sandpaper on wood.": "",
  "What is glacial till?": "",
  "Ice crystals that form on the surface of a glacier": "",
  "Water that flows from a melting glacier": "",
  "Unsorted sediment of all sizes deposited directly by glacial ice": "",
  "Sorted layers of sand and gravel deposited by glacial meltwater": "",
  "Glacial till is a mixture of unsorted sediment ranging from fine clay to large boulders that is deposited directly by glacial ice as it melts, unlike sorted sediment deposited by meltwater streams.": "",
  "What is a sediment budget?": "",
  "The cost of removing sediment from a river": "",
  "The balance between sediment being added to and removed from a system, determining whether an area gains or loses sediment": "",
  "The federal funding allocated for sediment research": "",
  "The total weight of sediment in a river at any given time": "",
  "A sediment budget accounts for the input, transport, and output of sediment in a system such as a beach or river, determining whether the area is gaining sediment (building up) or losing it (eroding).": "",
  "What does 'sorted sediment' mean?": "",
  "Sediment that has been artificially organized by scientists": "",
  "Sediment that has been separated by size during transport, with similar-sized particles deposited together": "",
  "Sediment that has been compressed into solid rock": "",
  "Sediment that contains only one type of mineral": "",
  "Sorted sediment consists of particles of similar sizes deposited together, which occurs naturally when water or wind separates particles by size during transport, with heavier particles dropping out first and lighter ones carried farther.": "",
  "After a major wildfire burns away all vegetation on a steep hillside, the next rainstorm washes enormous amounts of soil into the stream valley below. A town downstream notices the river running thick with mud and sediment filling their reservoir. What erosion principle explains this dramatic increase in sediment transport?": "",
  "The fire created new minerals that are lighter and easier to transport": "",
  "Without vegetation to hold the soil in place, rainwater easily erodes the exposed surface and carries massive amounts of sediment downhill": "",
  "Wildfires always increase the slope angle, causing more gravity-driven erosion": "",
  "The fire heated the soil so much that it chemically dissolved into liquid": "",
  "Vegetation roots anchor soil and plant cover intercepts raindrops, so removing vegetation by fire exposes bare soil directly to rainfall impact and runoff, dramatically increasing erosion rates and sediment delivery to streams.": "",
  "A coastal homeowner builds a jetty extending into the ocean from their property to protect their beach. Over the next few years, sand accumulates on one side of the jetty, but the neighbor's beach on the other side shrinks dramatically. What process explains this?": "",
  "The jetty interrupted longshore drift, trapping sand on the updrift side and starving the downdrift side of sediment": "",
  "The jetty absorbed all the wave energy, preventing any deposition": "",
  "Tidal currents reversed direction because of the jetty": "",
  "The jetty caused sea level to rise on one side": "",
  "Longshore drift continuously moves sand along the coast, and when a jetty blocks this flow, sand accumulates on the updrift side while the downdrift side is deprived of its normal sediment supply and erodes away.": "",
  "A geologist studying a river notices that near a mountain, the riverbed contains large boulders and gravel. Thirty miles downstream on a flat plain, the same river carries mostly fine sand and silt. What explains this change in sediment size along the river?": "",
  "Different rock types along the route produce different sediment sizes": "",
  "Wind erosion removes the larger particles from the downstream section": "",
  "As the river's velocity decreases downstream on the flatter terrain, it can only carry smaller particles, having already deposited the larger ones upstream": "",
  "Fish and aquatic organisms break down the larger particles into smaller ones": "",
  "Water velocity determines the size of sediment a river can carry; as the river moves from steep mountain terrain to a flat plain, it slows down and progressively deposits larger particles first, carrying only fine particles downstream.": "",
  "Farmers in the U.S. Midwest notice that after heavy spring rains, their freshly plowed fields develop deep gullies and lose significant topsoil to nearby streams. A neighboring farm using no-till practices and cover crops experiences much less soil loss. What erosion control principle is demonstrated?": "",
  "The cover crops absorb all the rainwater before it can reach the soil surface": "",
  "No-till farming changes the chemistry of rainwater so it cannot erode soil": "",
  "No-till farming makes the soil heavier so it cannot be moved": "",
  "Cover crops and undisturbed soil resist erosion because plant roots hold soil in place and residue protects the surface from raindrop impact": "",
  "No-till practices and cover crops protect soil from erosion by maintaining root structures that bind soil particles together and leaving plant residue on the surface to absorb the impact of raindrops and slow runoff.": "",
  "A dam is built across a river for hydroelectric power. After several decades, the reservoir behind the dam fills with sediment, and beaches downstream of the dam begin to disappear. What explains both of these observations?": "",
  "Evaporation from the reservoir dried out the downstream beaches": "",
  "The dam changed the type of rock in the riverbed": "",
  "The dam trapped sediment in the reservoir, preventing it from flowing downstream where it would normally replenish beaches": "",
  "The dam increased erosion both upstream and downstream equally": "",
  "Dams act as sediment traps, allowing particles to settle in the calm reservoir water while releasing sediment-free water downstream, which starves downstream beaches and channels of the sediment they need to maintain themselves.": "",
  "A team of scientists visits Iceland and observes a broad, flat plain covered with layers of fine sand, gravel, and braided stream channels extending from the front of a retreating glacier. What depositional feature are they observing?": "",
  "A loess deposit from wind-blown volcanic ash": "",
  "A river delta forming at the coast": "",
  "A glacial outwash plain formed by meltwater streams depositing sorted sediment": "",
  "An alluvial fan at the base of a non-glaciated mountain": "",
  "Glacial outwash plains form when meltwater streams flowing from a glacier deposit sorted layers of sand and gravel across a broad, flat area in front of the ice margin, creating braided stream networks.": "",
  "A city built on a river floodplain experiences a severe flood after record rainfall. Engineers propose building higher concrete levees to prevent future flooding. A geologist warns that while levees may protect this city, they could worsen flooding in downstream communities. Why?": "",
  "Levees cause chemical changes in the water that increase flooding": "",
  "Levees attract more rainfall to downstream areas": "",
  "Levees confine floodwater to the channel, increasing flow speed and volume downstream where the levees end": "",
  "Levees remove all water from the river permanently": "",
  "Levees prevent floodwater from spreading across the natural floodplain, forcing all the water through a narrow channel at higher velocity and volume, which can cause more severe flooding when the levees end downstream.": "",
  "A tourist visiting the Sahara Desert notices that the rock formations have smooth, sculpted shapes near ground level but are rough and jagged higher up. What erosion process explains this pattern?": "",
  "Flooding from rare desert storms polished only the lower portions": "",
  "Chemical weathering from rain is stronger near the ground": "",
  "Wind abrasion is concentrated near ground level where sand particles travel, smoothing lower surfaces while upper portions remain unaffected": "",
  "Animals rubbing against the lower rocks wore them smooth": "",
  "Wind-blown sand particles are heavy enough that they travel mostly within the first meter or two above the ground, concentrating abrasion at lower levels and leaving higher surfaces relatively unaffected by wind erosion.": "",
  "After a massive hurricane, a barrier island off the coast of North Carolina is completely breached, with ocean water flowing through a new inlet where houses once stood. However, satellite images show that new sand has been deposited further down the coast. What does this demonstrate about coastal erosion and deposition?": "",
  "Hurricanes create new sand from seawater minerals": "",
  "The barrier island was too old and simply collapsed from age": "",
  "The new sand deposit came from the ocean floor being pushed onto shore": "",
  "Sediment eroded from one area is transported and deposited in another, showing that erosion and deposition are linked processes that constantly reshape coastlines": "",
  "This scenario demonstrates the fundamental link between erosion and deposition: sediment removed by storm waves from one part of the coast is transported by currents and deposited elsewhere, constantly reshaping coastal landforms.": "",
  "A civil engineer is designing a new housing development on a hillside above a river valley. During site inspection, she notices that the hillside soil is thick clay on a steep slope, and the area receives heavy seasonal rainfall. She recommends extensive drainage systems, retaining walls, and preserving natural vegetation on the slope. What erosion and deposition risks is she trying to prevent?": "",
  "She is trying to stop the river from flooding uphill toward the development": "",
  "She is preventing potential slope failure and excessive sediment erosion that could wash clay downhill into the river, clogging waterways and damaging homes below": "",
  "She is concerned that wind erosion will blow the clay soil away": "",
  "She is worried about chemical weathering dissolving the house foundations": "",
  "Clay soils on steep slopes are highly susceptible to erosion and slope failure when saturated by heavy rainfall, so the engineer's measures aim to manage water drainage, stabilize the slope, and prevent sediment from eroding downhill.": ""
}